'''Desariee Starr Compton'''  (born [[February 21]], [[1989]]) is an American [[actress]] who goes professionally by the name '''Scout Taylor-Compton'''. She has appeared in numerous small television roles and in feature films such as ''[[Tomorrow is Today]]'' and ''[[Sleepover (film)|Sleepover]]''. Taylor-Compton has also starred in the horror films ''[[Wicked Little Things]]'' and ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'', which has garnered her the title of "[[scream queen]]".<ref name="MTV"/><ref name="Joblo"/><ref name="Teen"/>

Taylor-Compton recently finished filming the television movie ''Love's Unfolding Dream'' which is set to premiere on [[November 24]], [[2007]]. She has two more horror films yet to be released. The first, the 2008 film ''[[Pearblossom]]'' and the other is ''[[April Fool's Day (2009 film)|April Fool's Day]]'', a remake of the 1986 film of [[April Fool's Day (film)|same name]].

In addition to previously taking vocal lessons and singing the theme song for her 2001 film ''Chicken Night'', Taylor-Compton is also recording her debut rock album. 

==Personal life==
Taylor-Compton was born Desariee Starr Compton in [[Long Beach, California]],<ref name="IMDB">{{cite web| title= Scout Taylor-Compton| publisher= [[International Movie Database]]| url= http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0174021/bio | accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref> and is of [[Mexico|Mexican]] descent on her mother's side.<ref name="mother">{{cite news|last=Carmona|first=Josh|title=Apple Valley actress, 18, stars in ‘Halloween’|pages=|publisher=Daily Press|date=[[2007-09-23]]|url=http://www.vvdailypress.com/news/taylor_2945___article.html/compton_halloween.html|accessdate=2007-09-23}}</ref> Her father is a [[mortician]].<ref name="mortician">{{cite news|last=Barker|first=Lynn|title=Scout Taylor-Compton Turns Scream Queen|pages=|publisher=TeenHollywood|date=[[2007-08-28]]|url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/d.asp?r=157207&p=1|accessdate=2007-09-01}}</ref> Taylor-Compton explains about her father's profession, "[I] grew up in that whole [horror] genre and visiting my dad at the mortuary. I have no problem with that stuff. [...] whether it was a coffin or my dad bringing his work home. My friends would never want to come oveer because of that." She claims to be a [[tomboy]], once only having male friends and saying that much of free time when she was younger was occupied swimming, playing baseball, and rock-climbing.<ref name="Fangoria Sept">{{cite magazine| last= Turek| first= Ryan| title= Scout's Horror| publisher= [[Fangoria (magazine)|Fangoria]]| year= 2007| month= September}}</ref> 

Previous to acting, Taylor-Compton had been a competitive swimmer and had plans to participate in the [[AAU Junior Olympic Games|AAUJunior Olympics]], before focusing on her acting career.<ref name="Superior pics"/> In a 2003 biography, she was said to have enjoyed volleyball, cheerleading, dance, gymnastics and roller-blading as well. According to the biography she has had four cats named Sprocket, Jordan, Baby, Zooey, and two dogs, Bear and Lexi (a [[Chihuaha]]); currently, Taylor-Compton no longer has Sprocket or Bear.<ref name="teenmag">{{cite web| title= GET TO KNOW: SCOUT TAYLOR COMPTON| publisher= teenmag.com| url=http://www.missoandfriends.com/misso/thescoop/entertainment/interview_scouttaylorcompton.php| accessdate= 2007-09-25}}</ref> Also, after an interview with [[Ron Howard]], she had aspirations to become a film director.<ref name="SC Bio"/> 

On the morning of [[August 12]], [[2005]], Taylor-Compton disappeared from her home in [[Apple Valley]], [[California]] and was reported missing after an apparent family disagreement; she was missing for a total of two weeks. She had been sleeping in a playground before meeting a family who offered her shelter. After a High School coach told police that one of his students had been telling of having an actress in his home, Taylor-Compton was found in good health, and there were no reports of criminal activity in her time missing. In that time she had dyed her hair black and hid when officers arrived on scene, but was soon returned to her parents after speaking with an officer.<ref>{{cite web| title= Runaway teen actress slept at park| publisher= [[MSN]]| url= http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/9089736/ | date= [[2005-09-26]]| accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref> At the time, Taylor-Compton was homeschooled with a 4.0 grade point average.<ref name= "Superior pics">{{cite web| title= Scout Taylor-Compton| publisher= superiorpics.com| url= http://www.superiorpics.com/scout_taylor_compton/ | accessdate= 2007-09-15}}</ref>

Taylor-Compton is a fan of horror films, her favorite being the ''[[Child's Play]]'' series<ref name="mother"/>, and she has also said, "I love [the characters] [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael]] [Myers], [[Jason Vorhees|Jason]] [Vorhees] and [[Chucky (Child's Play)|Chucky]]."<ref name="Fangoria Sept"/> She also enjoys other horror films including ''[[Thir13en Ghosts]]''<ref name="SC Bio"/>, ''[[Halloween 4]]'' and ''[[Halloween 5]]'', and she has claimed to be a fan of the lead actress of the latter two films [[Danielle Harris]];<ref>{{cite web| title= BDTV Exclusive: Interview With 'Halloween' Star Scout Taylor-Compton | publisher= bloody-disgusting.com| url= http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/bdtv/Player.php?id=1105 | accessdate= 2007-09-15}}</ref> the two later went onto appear together in the [[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween remake]]. 

Taylor-Compton enjoys punk rock music including [[The Misfits]], [[Alkaline Trio]], [[NOFX]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Kelly Osbourne]] and [[Nickelback]].<ref name="mortician"/> She enjoys shopping at [[Urban Outfitters]],  and watching [[MTV]] and [[The History Channel]]; her favorite television program is [[Degrassi]].<ref name="teenmag"/>

She is also a celebrity youth member of the charity group [[Kids With a Cause]] and takes part in charity events for the organization.

After acting, Taylor-Compton has expressed interest in becoming a mortician and coroner, saying, "Maybe in the future I will go to college and study that."<ref name="LA Journal"/>

==Career==
===Acting===
In 1998, Taylor-Compton began her acting career with an appearance in the film ''A.W.O.L.'' with [[David Morse (actor)|David Morse]], and later in the short film ''Thursday Afternoon''. She later went on to have small roles in both television and film including ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[Fraiser]]'', ''[[The Guardian (TV series)|The Guardian]]'' and ''[[The Division]]''. She also appeared in several student films, commercials for products including Fuji Film and the [[Disney Cruise Line]], and various skits on [[The Jay Leno Show]].<ref name="IMDB Other">{{cite web| title=Other works for Scout Taylor-Compton| publisher= [[International Movie Database]]| url= http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0174021/otherworks | accessdate= 2007-09-15}}</reF> November 2000 saw Taylor-Compton make her stage debut as the title character in a production of ''[[Annie Warbucks]]'' at The Grove Theatre in [[Upland, California]], and a stage production  of ''[[Footloose]]'' at the Simi Valley Cultural Arts Center.<ref name="SC Bio"/> In 2001, had a small recurring role in the television series ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'', appearing in a total of four episodes until 2004 with garnered her a nomination for "Best Performance in a TV Series - Recurring Young Actress".<ref name="Superior pics"/> She also made a comedic appearance in the 2003 film ''Four Fingers of the Dragon'' playing herself auditioning for a role in a fictional [[Kung Fu]] film.<ref name="SC Bio">{{cite web| title= Biography and Facts| publisher= celebritykidz.com| url= http://www.celebritykidz.com/scoutcompton/bio.htm | accessdate= 2007-09-15}}</ref> Later in 2004, she appeared in the teen comedy ''[[Sleepover (film)|Sleepover]]'' in which she was nominated along with her cast for "Best Performance in a Feature Film - Young Ensemble Cast" at the Young Artists Award. The film did mediocre in the box office, totaling a gross of $9,436,390.<ref>{{cite web| title= Sleepover (2004)| publisher= Boxofficemojo.com| url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sleepover.htm | accessdate= 2007-09-11}}</ref> Following ''Sleepover'', she appeared in numerous television series including ''Hidden Howie'', ''[[Unfabulous]]'' (2 episodes), ''[[Cold Case]]'', ''[[That's So Raven]]'', ''[[Charmed (TV series)| Charmed]]'' (7 episodes) and ''[[Without a Trace]]'' (in which she portrayed a runaway teenager). 

In 2006 Taylor-Compton appeared in the film ''The Honeyfields''. That year as well, she starred in the drama ''[[Tomorrow is Today]]'' and the horror film ''[[Wicked Little Things]]''. ''Tomorrow is Today'' features Taylor-Compton as Julie Peterson, a girl who saves the life of and befriends a hapless drifter. The film went on to win over 6 awards at various festivals which included the California Independent Film Festival, the Garden State Film Festival, Method Fest, and the Rhode Island International Film Festival. Taylor-Compton won "Best Actress" for her performance in the film at Method Fest.<ref name="Awards">{{cite web| title= Tomorrow is Today| publisher= [[International Movie Database]]| url= http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462573/awards | accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref> ''Wicked Little Things'' saw Taylor-Compton star as Sarah Tunny in [[8 Films to Die For|After Dark's 8 Films to Die For]]. Following these films, she appeared in the television series ''[[Standoff (TV series)|Standoff]]'' and ''[[Close to Home]]''.

[[Image:LaurieStrode2007.jpg|thumb|Taylor-Compton as [[Laurie Strode]] in ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]''.]]
In 2007 Taylor-Compton appeared in the film ''[[An American Crime]]'' which told the true story of suburban housewife [[Gertrude Baniszewski]], whom had kept a teenage girl locked in the basement of her [[Indiana]] home during the 1960s. After losing the lead role in the [[Pang Brothers]] film ''[[The Messengers]]'' to [[Kristen Stewart]],<ref name="Superior pics"/> Taylor-Compton then returned to the horror genre as [[Laurie Strode]] in [[Rob Zombie]]'s [[Halloween (2007 film)|remake]] of the classic ''[[Halloween (film)|Halloween]]''. She endured a long audition process, but as director Zombie explains, "Scout was my first choice. There was just something about her; he had a genuine quality. She didn't seem actor-y."<ref name="Fangoria Sept"/> Bill Gibron of [[PopMatters]] gave the film a 9 out of 10 and said the film was "brilliant" and "a stroke of slice and dice genius."<ref>{{cite web| title= Short Cuts - In Theaters: Halloween (2007)| publisher=[[PopMatters]]| url= http://www.popmatters.com/pm/blogs/shortends_post/47762/short-cuts-in-theaters-halloween-2007/ |accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref> The film broke box-office records as the highest grossing film on the Labor Day weekend. It pulled in $31 million dollars over the holiday weekend, surpassing the record set in 2005 by [[Transporter 2]] of $20.1 million dollars. Furthermore, it surpassed the record set in 1999 by [[The Sixth Sense]] of $29 million dollars (in its fifth weekend), making it the highest grossing film over the Labor Day weekend ever.<ref name="Forbes">{{cite web| title= `Halloween' Scares Up $31 Million Debut| publisher= [[Forbes|Forbes.com]]| url= http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/09/03/ap4076822.html | accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref>  It currently stands as the highest grossing overall film in the [[Halloween (film series)|Halloween franchise]].<ref name="The Numbers">{{cite web| last=Carroll| first=Larry| title= Box Office History for Halloween Movies| publisher= the-numbers.com| url= http://the-numbers.com/movies/series/Halloween.php | accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref> Because of her appearance in the horror genre, Taylor Compton has been called a "[[scream queen]]".<ref name="MTV">{{cite web| title= 'Halloween' Star Scout Taylor-Compton Calls Michael Myers 'Cute,' Talks Sequel| publisher=[[MTV|MTV.com]]| url= http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1554614/story.jhtml | date= [[2007-03-15]]| accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref><ref name="Teen">{{cite web| title= Scout Taylor-Compton Turns Scream Queen| publisher= TeenHollywood.com| url= http://shaw.teenhollywood.com/d.asp?r=157207 | accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref><ref name="Joblo">{{cite web| title= INT: Scout Taylor Compton| publisher= joblo.com| url= http://www.joblo.com/index.php?id=17492 | accessdate= 2007-09-10}}</ref>

Taylor-Compton recently finished filming the television movie ''Love's Unfolding Dream'' which is set to premiere on [[November 24]], [[2007]]. She will also appear in another television film, ''Deadly Suspicion'' with [[Marilu Henner]]. She has two horror films yet to be released. The first is the 2008 film ''[[Pearblossom (film)|Pearblossom]]'' in which she will star as Carrie Lain. The other is ''[[April Fool's Day (2009 film)|April Fool's Day]]'' a remake of the 1986 film of [[April Fool's Day (film)|same name]]. Taylor-Compton explains on the starring in the role of Torrance: "I'll just be playing another wholesome 'good girl' that screams a lot."<ref name="mother"/> ''April Fool's Day'' is expected for release in 2009.

In an interview conducted in July 2007, Taylor-Compton reported that after completing ''April Fool's Day'', she wants to stay away from roles in the horror genre for her next few projects. Although she has received many horror film scripts, Taylor-Compton, cites appearing in many horror films in a short period of time as the reason.<ref>{{cite web| title= Scout Taylor-Compton| publisher= youtube.com| url= http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh5YCB_T6B0| accessdate= 2007-09-22}}</ref> She has recently been influenced by the career of [[Scarlett Johansson]], wanting to chose scripts and roles based on personal interest as she views Johansson does. Taylor-Compton went onto explain, "That’s what I kind of want to do. I love just being passionate about something rather than just caring about the money or who’s in the movie.<ref name="LA Journal"/>

===Other work===
In 1998 she appeared in The Adventures of Lily music video for "Femme Fatale". In 2001, Taylor Compton provided voice overs for ''[[I Am Sam]]'', and continued with voice over work with appearances in ''[[The Core]]'' in 2003 and ''[[The Princess Diaries 2: Royal Engagement]]'' in 2004. The next year in 2005, she provided voice over work for the teen hero comedy ''[[Sky High]]''. In 2001, she sang the theme song "Jet Set" for her film ''Chicken Night''<ref name="SC Bio"/> and later that year she appeared in the music video for the [[Nine Inch Nails]] song "[[The Fragile]]". 2002 saw Taylor-Compton appearing briefly in the [[Will Smith]] music video for the song "Black Suits Comin' (Nod Ya Head)" for the [[Men in Black 2]] Soundtrack. She also appeared in the music video for the song "[http://youtube.com/watch?v=XBQmF0gkUYs Sweet Valentine]" by the band Born the Sky in 2007.

In 2003, Taylor-Compton had taken vocal lessons with Diane Gillespie and Vocal Power Institute. She had also taken guitar, drums, and keyboard lessons, and was member a theatre group called "Shenanigans," where she performed and took weekly tap and jazz lessons.<ref name="SC Bio"/> Taylor-Compton also attended the [[Hollywood Pop Academy]] for additional vocal training.<ref>{{cite web| title= Success Stories| publisher= hollywoodpopacademy.com| url= http://www.hollywoodpopacademy.com/ssp/success | accessdate= 2007-09-19}}</ref>

Taylor-Compton is currently working on her debut punk rock/pop album,<ref name="IMDB"/> in which she will sing and play drums. She cites [[Cyndi Lauper]] as an influence in her singing.<ref name="LA Journal">{{cite web| title= An interview with Scout Taylor-Compton | publisher= losangelesjournal.com| url= http://www.losangelesjournal.com/new/articles-view-3-481 | accessdate= 2007-09-26}}</ref> Taylor-Compton will be working with [[ERA Productions]] and "will begin working with a very well-known punk/pop singer."<ref name="Superior pics"/> She has also stated that singing is a side project and "is just a little talent that I have on the side and if it does something then I'll do that but I'm not gonna give up acting."<ref name="mortician"/>

